The list of individuals who occupied these seats is also, predictably, [incomplete](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Lists). August 2008. A perpetual work in progress, like everything else.

During the period of the multi-member constituency, from 1921 to 1929, it was simply referred to as DOWN. A single entity, before the divisions began.

#### Dáil Éireann: A Republican Theoretical Construct

In 1921, [Sinn Féin](/Sinn_F%C3%A9in) made a decision. They decided to participate in the UK-sanctioned elections for the [Northern Ireland House of Commons](/Northern_Ireland_House_of_Commons) and the [House of Commons of Southern Ireland](/House_of_Commons_of_Southern_Ireland). They saw it as a way to register a vote, a poll, for the [Irish Republic](/Irish_Republic)'s [Second Dáil](/Second_D%C3%A1il). In this republican framework, this particular stretch of [County Down](/County_Down) was designated as the eight-member Dáil constituency of Down. A theoretical construct, a ghost in the machine of parliamentary representation.

